{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17489706","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17489706"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T04:26:55+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T04:26:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"723"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"723","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/723"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.74,0.11,0.06,0.06,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"723"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52028"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"723","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/723"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"723"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37341"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"251"},{"type":"tags","id":"517"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"3549"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"9267"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5281"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6384"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14942"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43810"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52028","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/52028"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 47-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a two-month history of anorexia, post-prandial epigastric discomfort and weight loss. She has tried over-the-counter antacids without relief. Over the last two weeks, she has been vomiting after meals and occasionally brings up food eaten the previous day. She reports fatigue and dark-coloured stools recently. She has been taking ibuprofen intermittently over the last three months for knee pain. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears unwell. Her pulse rate is 80/min, blood pressure 115/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. Her conjunctivae are pale. The rest of the physical examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Gastroscopy","Urea breath test","Faecal occult blood test","Barium swallow","Abdominal ultrasound"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with symptoms suggestive of partial malignant gastric outlet obstruction. The most appropriate initial investigation is \u003Cstrong\u003Egastroscopy\u003C/strong\u003E. This allows direct visualization of the upper gastrointestinal tract and enables biopsy of any suspicious lesions. Gastroscopy is particularly indicated given the presence of several red flags: unintentional weight loss, persistent vomiting, and possible melena (dark-coloured stools).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Eurea breath test\u003C/strong\u003E is used to detect Helicobacter pylori infection. While H. pylori is a risk factor for gastric cancer, this test would be less appropriate as the initial investigation given the concerning symptoms that require direct visualization of the stomach. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Efaecal occult blood test\u003C/strong\u003E is generally indicated for colorectal cancer screening. While this patient reports dark stools, suggesting possible upper GI bleeding, the other symptoms point more strongly towards an upper GI pathology..\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Ebarium swallow\u003C/strong\u003E can be used to evaluate the upper GI tract, but it has several disadvantages compared to gastroscopy. It doesn\u0027t allow for tissue biopsy, may miss small lesions, and can interfere with subsequent endoscopy if performed first. Given the high suspicion for malignancy, gastroscopy is preferred.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAbdominal ultrasound\u003C/strong\u003E would be more appropriate if biliary tract pathology was suspected. It\u0027s not the best initial test for evaluating suspected upper GI malignancy or obstruction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn summary, given the patient\u0027s age, symptoms suggestive of gastric outlet obstruction, and red flags (weight loss, persistent vomiting, possible melena), gastroscopy is the most appropriate next investigation. It allows for direct visualization of the upper GI tract and biopsy of any suspicious lesions, which is crucial for diagnosing potential malignancies.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Upper gastrointestinal tract endoscopy is indicated in patients who present with red flags in addition to dyspepsia.","Gastroscopy is the preferred initial investigation for suspected upper gastrointestinal malignancy, offering direct visualization and biopsy capabilities."],"references":["American Cancer Society. Colorectal Cancer Signs and Symptoms. https://www.cancer.org/cancer/colon-rectal-cancer/detection-diagnosis-staging/signs-and-symptoms.html","Ahmed Madisch, Viola Andresen, Paul Enck, Joachim Labenz, Thomas Frieling, Michael Schemann. The Diagnosis and Treatment of Functional Dyspepsia. Deutsches Aerzteblatt Online .2018. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5938438/","Sexton RE, Al Hallak MN, Diab M, Azmi AS. Gastric cancer: a comprehensive review of current and future treatment strategies. Cancer and Metastasis Reviews .2020; 39(4): p.1179-1203. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/32894370/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37341"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"723"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37341","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/37341"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-02T09:26:35+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-02T09:27:34+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"723"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52028"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"